'''Hierophylakes''', also known as '''hierodidaskaloi''', '''hieronomoi''', or '''hierophantai''',<ref>[[Dionysius of Halicarnassus]] (translated by [[Earnest Cary]]) – [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=spolCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT172&dq=hierophylakes&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAmoVChMI6qes-tHYxgIVxhbbCh2CUwvp#v=onepage&q=hierophylakes&f=false The Roman Antiquities] Aeterna Press 30 May 2015  [Retrieved 2015-07-13]</ref> were priests for the [[Eumolpidai]]<ref name="W.S. Bubelis">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=szY5qMHmXx8C&pg=PA96&dq=hierophantai&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCMQ6AEwAGoVChMIh8eAutbYxgIVRgnbCh0nPACL#v=onepage&q=hierophantai&f=false|title=Inheritance, Priesthoods, and Succession in Classical Athens:the Hierophantai of the Eumolpidai (in) Families in the Greco-Roman World|publisher=A&C Black 2 Feb 2012, 194 pages, {{ISBN|1-4411-3927-3}}|author=W.S. Bubelis ( edited by R. Laurence, A. Stromberg)|accessdate=2015-07-13}}</ref> involved in performing acts of [[sacrifice]].<ref>Stéphanie Paul (edited by [[Marietta Horster]], Anja Klöckner) – [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ndjmBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA268&dq=hierophylakes&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDwQ6AEwBWoVChMIl5zBqNTYxgIVLFrbCh3h8g5q#v=onepage&q=hierophylakes&f=false Cities and Priests: Cult Personnel in Asia Minor and the Aegean Islands from the Hellenistic to the Imperial Period] Volume 64 of ''Religionsgeschichtliche Versuche und Vorarbeiten'', Walter de Gruyter 1 Jan 2014, 380 pages, {{ISBN|3-11-031848-2}} [Retrieved 2015-07-13]</ref>

[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]] stated that new hierophantai were elected every [[quadrennial]], and so individuals did not maintain an existence within this role for their life-time. He also stated that they might marry if they wished to do so known as, lambanein gynaika.<ref name="W.S. Bubelis" />

